      <byline class="print_byline">By Stuart Elliott</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Elliott, Stuart</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>T J Maxx, discount retailer owned by TJX Companies, and advertising agency Holland Mark Edmund Ingalls are parting ways after 24 years; spending was estimated at $20 million (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>T. J. Maxx, the discount retailer owned by the TJX Companies, and Holland Mark Edmund Ingalls in Boston are parting ways after 24 years. Spending was estimated at $20 million.</p>
        <p>''It was their decision,'' said Bill Davis, chief executive at Holland Mark.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>T. J. Maxx, the discount retailer owned by the TJX Companies, and Holland Mark Edmund Ingalls in Boston are parting ways after 24 years. Spending was estimated at $20 million.</p>
        <p>''It was their decision,'' said Bill Davis, chief executive at Holland Mark.</p>
        <p>Sherry Lang, a spokeswoman for TJX in Framingham, Mass., said the company had begun a review; a decision is expected in about two months.</p>
        <p>THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING -- ADDENDA</p>
      </block>
